            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What is the HEART score?</h2>
              <p>
                The HEART score is a validated clinical tool used to
                risk‑stratify adult patients presenting to the emergency
                department with chest pain suggestive of acute coronary syndrome
                (ACS). It predicts the short‑term risk of major adverse cardiac
                events (MACE), typically within 30 days, including myocardial
                infarction, need for revascularization, and death.
              </p>
              <p>HEART is an acronym for:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>H</strong>istory</li>
                <li><strong>E</strong>CG</li>
                <li><strong>A</strong>ge</li>
                <li><strong>R</strong>isk factors</li>
                <li><strong>T</strong>roponin</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>HEART score components and scoring</h2>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-2">Total HEART score</p>
                <p>\[ \text{HEART} = H + E + A + R + T \]</p>
                <ul class="mt-2">
                  <li><strong>H (History):</strong> 0–2 points</li>
                  <li><strong>E (ECG):</strong> 0–2 points</li>
                  <li><strong>A (Age):</strong> 0–2 points</li>
                  <li><strong>R (Risk factors):</strong> 0–2 points</li>
                  <li><strong>T (Troponin):</strong> 0–2 points</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2">Minimum score: 0, maximum score: 10.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>History (H)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0 points:</strong> Slightly suspicious – atypical
                  features, alternative diagnosis more likely.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 point:</strong> Moderately suspicious – mixed
                  typical and atypical features.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2 points:</strong> Highly suspicious – classic
                  ischemic chest pain (e.g., pressure, exertional, radiating,
                  associated diaphoresis or dyspnea).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>ECG (E)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>0 points:</strong> Normal ECG.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 point:</strong> Nonspecific repolarization
                  abnormalities, bundle branch block, or unchanged chronic
                  changes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2 points:</strong> Significant ST‑segment depression
                  compatible with ischemia.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Age (A)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>0 points:</strong> &lt; 45 years</li>
                <li><strong>1 point:</strong> 45–65 years</li>
                <li><strong>2 points:</strong> &gt; 65 years</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Risk factors (R)</h3>
              <p>Common cardiovascular risk factors include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Diabetes mellitus</li>
                <li>Current or recent smoking</li>
                <li>Hypertension</li>
                <li>Hyperlipidemia</li>
                <li>Obesity</li>
                <li>
                  Positive family history of premature coronary artery disease
                </li>
                <li>
                  Known atherosclerotic disease (prior MI, PCI/CABG, stroke, or
                  peripheral arterial disease)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0 points:</strong> No risk factors or only 1 risk
                  factor.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 point:</strong> 2–3 risk factors or known
                  atherosclerotic disease.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2 points:</strong> &ge; 3 risk factors or multiple
                  significant comorbidities.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Troponin (T)</h3>
              <p>
                Troponin is scored relative to the upper reference limit (URL)
                of your local assay:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0 points:</strong> Troponin ≤ URL (within normal
                  range).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1 point:</strong> Troponin &gt; URL but ≤ 3× URL.
                </li>
                <li><strong>2 points:</strong> Troponin &gt; 3× URL.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator allows you to enter both the measured troponin
                and the URL so that the relative elevation is calculated
                automatically.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical use and limitations</h2>
              <p>
                The HEART score has been validated in multiple cohorts and is
                widely used to support decision‑making in chest pain units and
                emergency departments. It is particularly helpful for
                identifying low‑risk patients who may be safely discharged after
                appropriate evaluation.
              </p>
              <p>However, it has important limitations:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  It is intended for <strong>adult</strong> patients with chest
                  pain where ACS is a diagnostic consideration.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It should not be used in patients with clear STEMI,
                  hemodynamic instability, or obvious alternative diagnoses.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> replace serial ECGs, serial
                  troponins, or comprehensive clinical assessment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Local protocols, available troponin assays (including
                  high‑sensitivity assays), and population characteristics may
                  affect performance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always apply the HEART score within the context of your
                institution’s chest pain pathway and consult cardiology or
                senior clinicians when in doubt.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I use high‑sensitivity troponin with the HEART score?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The HEART score can be used with either conventional or
                high‑sensitivity troponin assays, as long as you use the correct
                upper reference limit (URL) for your lab. Some institutions have
                adapted HEART into pathways that incorporate serial
                high‑sensitivity troponin measurements and accelerated
                diagnostic protocols.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should troponin be repeated?</h3>
              <p>
                Many protocols repeat troponin at 1–3 hours after the initial
                sample, especially in low‑to‑intermediate risk patients. The
                exact timing and number of measurements depend on your local
                guidelines and the specific troponin assay used.
              </p>

              <h3>Is a low HEART score enough to discharge a patient?</h3>
              <p>
                A HEART score of 0–3 is associated with a low risk of 30‑day
                MACE, but discharge decisions must also consider:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Serial ECG and troponin results</li>
                <li>Symptom evolution and response to treatment</li>
                <li>Comorbidities and social factors</li>
                <li>Availability of timely outpatient follow‑up</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the HEART score as one piece of the overall clinical
                picture, not as a stand‑alone rule.
              </p>

